{
  "id": "objects",
  "title": "JS Objects",
  "group": "JS Objects",
  "content": [
    { "type": "h1", "text": "JavaScript Objects" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "Objects are used to store keyed collections of data. An object is a collection of properties (key-value pairs), where values can be data or functions (methods)." },
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Creating an Object" },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Object Literal", "code": [
      "const person = {",
      "    firstName: \"John\",",
      "    lastName:  \"Doe\",",
      "    age:       30,",
      "    isStudent: false,",
      "};",
      "",
      "console.log(person);",
      "console.log(person.firstName);   // dot notation",
      "console.log(person[\"age\"]);       // bracket notation"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Accessing Properties" },
    { "type": "table", "rows": [
      ["Notation",  "Syntax",              "Use When"],
      ["Dot",       "obj.propertyName",    "Key is a valid identifier"],
      ["Bracket",   "obj[\"key\"]",        "Key has spaces / is dynamic"]
    ]},
    { "type": "example", "title": "Dot vs Bracket Notation", "code": [
      "const car = { make: \"Toyota\", model: \"Camry\", year: 2022 };",
      "",
      "console.log(car.make);       // Toyota",
      "console.log(car[\"model\"]);   // Camry",
      "",
      "// Dynamic key with bracket notation:",
      "let prop = \"year\";",
      "console.log(car[prop]);      // 2022"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Adding and Modifying Properties" },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Mutating Objects", "code": [
      "const user = { name: \"Alice\" };",
      "",
      "user.age  = 28;         // add new property",
      "user.name = \"Alicia\";   // modify existing property",
      "console.log(user);      // { name: \"Alicia\", age: 28 }",
      "",
      "delete user.age;        // remove a property",
      "console.log(user);      // { name: \"Alicia\" }"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Methods — Functions Inside Objects" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "A method is a function stored as an object property. Inside methods, this refers to the object." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Object Methods", "code": [
      "const calculator = {",
      "    value: 0,",
      "    add(n)      { this.value += n; return this; },",
      "    subtract(n) { this.value -= n; return this; },",
      "    result()    { return this.value; },",
      "};",
      "",
      "calculator.add(10).add(5).subtract(3);",
      "console.log(calculator.result());   // 12"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Looping Over an Object" },
    { "type": "example", "title": "for...in and Object Helpers", "code": [
      "const scores = { math: 95, english: 88, science: 92 };",
      "",
      "for (let subject in scores) {",
      "    console.log(subject + \": \" + scores[subject]);",
      "}",
      "",
      "console.log(Object.keys(scores));    // [\"math\", \"english\", \"science\"]",
      "console.log(Object.values(scores));  // [95, 88, 92]",
      "console.log(Object.entries(scores)); // [[\"math\",95], ...]"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Nested Objects" },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Nested Objects", "code": [
      "const company = {",
      "    name: \"Acme\",",
      "    address: {",
      "        street: \"123 Main St\",",
      "        city:   \"Springfield\",",
      "    },",
      "    employees: [\"Alice\", \"Bob\", \"Carol\"],",
      "};",
      "",
      "console.log(company.name);",
      "console.log(company.address.city);",
      "console.log(company.employees[0]);"
    ]},
    { "type": "note", "text": "Objects declared with const can still have their properties changed — const only prevents reassigning the variable itself." },
    { "type": "exercise", "question": "How do you access a property called 'name' on an object called person?", "options": ["person->name", "person::name", "person.name", "person#name"], "answer": 2 }
  ]
}
